In the heating mode, the sorbents LiCl@HGAFs capture water molecules and release adsorption heat (Qads) to the house for indoor heating. As the adsorbent will become saturated with water, regeneration is required. Energy is taken up at a relatively high temperature (Qregen) to desorb the water, which is subsequently condensed, releasing heat at an intermediate temperature (Qcon) to the house. Both of the released Qads and Qcon contribute to indoor heating. In the cooling mode, heat is taken up from the house by the evaporation of the working fluid (Qeva), driven by the water sorption of the sorbents LiCl@HGAFs. Therefore, one can operate such a switchable sorption cycle as a heat pump to produce heating using Qcon and Qads, or to produce cooling by using Qeva.
